======================================================================
PART 1: THE TRIVIAL MODULAR LAW AND BEYOND
======================================================================

THEOREM (trivial): I(CG(T), x) ≡ 1 (mod x) for ALL T.
  Proof: I = 1 + α₁x + α₂x² + ... ≡ 1 (mod x).  □

This explains:
  I(CG, 2) ≡ 1 (mod 2)  → H is always odd (Rédei)
  I(CG, 6) ≡ 1 (mod 6)
  I(CG, 10) ≡ 1 (mod 10)
  I(CG, 11) ≡ 1 (mod 11)

DEEPER QUESTION: When is I(CG, x) ≡ 1 (mod x²)?
  I ≡ 1 + α₁x (mod x²), so this holds ⟺ α₁ ≡ 0 (mod x).

