======================================================================
PART 5: RÉDEI AS A SPECIAL CASE
======================================================================

GENERALIZED RÉDEI:
  For EVERY positive integer x:
    I(CG(T), x) ≡ 1 (mod x)

  At x=2: H ≡ 1 (mod 2)    ← Rédei's theorem
  At x=3: I₃ ≡ 1 (mod 3)
  At x=6: I₆ ≡ 1 (mod 6)
  At x=10: I₁₀ ≡ 1 (mod 10)
  At x=11: I₁₁ ≡ 1 (mod 11)

  This is trivial from I = 1 + α₁x + α₂x² + ...,
  but it gives a UNIFORM PERSPECTIVE on all modular results!

  The 2-adic and 3-adic towers are then about the REFINEMENT:
    mod x gives the 'Rédei level' (trivial)
    mod x² requires α₁ mod x (cycle count modular structure)
    mod x³ requires α₁ mod x² AND α₂ mod x
    etc.

THE ALPHA-TOWER CORRESPONDENCE:
  I(CG, x) mod x^k is determined by (α₁ mod x^{k-1}, α₂ mod x^{k-2}, ..., α_{k-1} mod x)

  For x=2 (OCF):
    mod 2:  always 1 (Rédei)
    mod 4:  determined by α₁ mod 2
    mod 8:  determined by α₁ mod 4, α₂ mod 2
    mod 16: determined by α₁ mod 8, α₂ mod 4, α₃ mod 2

  For x=3:
    mod 3:  always 1
    mod 9:  determined by α₁ mod 3
    mod 27: determined by α₁ mod 9, α₂ mod 3

