======================================================================
PART 7: JACOBSTHAL DENOMINATORS AND I(CG, k(k-1))
======================================================================

At x = k(k-1), does (2k-1) divide (I(CG,x)-1)/x = α₁ + α₂x + ...?
  This would mean I(CG,x) ≡ 1 (mod x·(2k-1))

  k=2, x=  2, denom=3: (I-1)/x mod 3 = [0, 1, 2]
  k=3, x=  6, denom=5: (I-1)/x mod 5 = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]
  k=4, x= 12, denom=7: (I-1)/x mod 7 = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
  k=5, x= 20, denom=9: (I-1)/x mod 9 = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
  k=6, x= 30, denom=11: (I-1)/x mod 11 = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
  k=7, x= 42, denom=13: (I-1)/x mod 13 = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]

So (2k-1) does NOT universally divide (I-1)/x.
The Jacobsthal denominator is NOT an extra divisor of I(CG,x)-1 beyond x itself.

Does 2x | (I(CG,x) - 1)?
  x=  2: (I-1) mod 2x=4: residues = [0, 2]
  x=  3: (I-1) mod 2x=6: residues = [0, 3]
  x=  6: (I-1) mod 2x=12: residues = [0, 6]
  x=  7: (I-1) mod 2x=14: residues = [0, 7]
  x=  8: (I-1) mod 2x=16: residues = [0, 8]
  x= 10: (I-1) mod 2x=20: residues = [0, 10]
  x= 11: (I-1) mod 2x=22: residues = [0, 11]
  x= 12: (I-1) mod 2x=24: residues = [0, 12]
  x= 42: (I-1) mod 2x=84: residues = [0, 42]

======================================================================
PART 8: THE RECURRENCE VIEW OF MOD STRUCTURE
======================================================================

SEEING MOD RESULTS AS RECURRENCES:

  I(CG, x) mod x satisfies a 'constant recurrence': always 1.
  This is the simplest possible recurrence.

  I(CG, 2) mod 4 satisfies: value ∈ {1, 3}
  The 'recurrence' on the conflict graph: each vertex adds 0 or 2 mod 4.

  I(CG, x) mod x² satisfies: value ∈ {1, 1+x, 1+2x, ..., 1+(x-1)x}
  = {1 + kx : k = α₁ mod x}
  So the 'recurrence' at the x² level has x states.

  THE 2-STATE AND 3-STATE RECURRENCES:
  x=2, mod 4: 2 states (H ≡ 1 or 3 mod 4)
  x=3, mod 9: 3 states (I₃ ≡ 1, 4, or 7 mod 9)
  x=2, mod 8: 4 states (H ≡ 1, 3, 5, or 7 mod 8)
  x=3, mod 27: up to 9 states

  The number of states at level k = x^{k-1}
  For x=2: 1, 2, 4, 8, ...   (powers of 2)
  For x=3: 1, 3, 9, 27, ...  (powers of 3)

  This IS the 2-adic and 3-adic tower structure!
  The 'keys to the universe' (2 and 3) determine the STATE SPACE
  of the modular recurrences at every level.

======================================================================
SUMMARY: THE NUMBER HIERARCHY IN TOURNAMENT THEORY
======================================================================

  I(CG, x) ≡ 1 (mod x) for ALL x, ALL tournaments.
  This is the UNIVERSAL MODULAR LAW (generalized Rédei).

  Rédei's theorem (H odd) is just the x=2 case.

  The x-adic tower I(CG, x) mod x^k gives a k-level
  description of the tournament's cycle structure,
  where the number of states at level k is x^{k-1}.

  For x=2: the 2-adic tower captures α₁ mod 2^{k-1}, etc.
  For x=3: the 3-adic tower captures the topological structure.
  These two towers together (via CRT) capture EVERYTHING,
  because 2 and 3 are coprime and generate all integers via
  the 2-adic × 3-adic product.

  The hierarchy 1 → (2,3) → (7,8) → (10,11) tracks
  how cycle packing complexity grows:
  • At n ≤ 7: single-level packing (only (3,3) pairs)
  • At n = 8: first cross-level packing ((3,5) pairs)
  • At n = 10: first two-5-cycle packing (5+5=10)
  • At n = 11: first perfect 3-part packing (3+3+5=11)

Done.
